<$fill $name="body">

!!! Why two plugins instead of bundling the player into mindmap?

Because "play a sequence of tiddlers" is broader than "play mindmap slides". A separate player keeps the data shape (filters yielding tiddlers) decoupled from the data source (mindmap, a tagged set, a generated list, a Trello-style board, anything else). Mindmap supplies the filter operator that flattens a presentation into slide titles; the player doesn't know or care where those titles came from.

!!! How does the deep-dive work — am I just opening tiddlers?

Yes — clicking a wikitext link inside a slide //navigates inside the overlay//. The widget intercepts the click, pushes the current location onto an internal stack, and re-renders the stage with the linked tiddler as a one-shot slide (using the `default` layout). The breadcrumb at the top shows the depth; click any segment to pop back, or use Esc which pops one level at a time. Once the stack is empty, Esc closes the overlay.

!!! Can the player remember my position across reloads?

No — navigation state is in-memory only by design. A presentation is a single live session; mid-session reloads aren't a use-case we support. If you need bookmarkable slide positions, write a thin wrapper that mirrors the state into a `$:/state/` tiddler.

!!! How big can a deck be?

Practically unlimited — only the current slide renders. Decks of hundreds of slides are fine. Decks of thousands of slides will be fine to play but slow to //compute the grid// (the widget evaluates the filter once and walks every result to read its section-field).

!!! Why does Space behave differently from →?

`→` always moves to the next section (jumping past any remaining vertical slides). `Space` is //linear//: it goes down within the current section first, only jumping right when the bottom of the section is reached. That mirrors reveal.js and matches the "walk the entire deck" mental model.

!!! Why does Esc not close immediately when I've dived deep?

So you can dive into a referenced tiddler during a Q&A, then Esc back to where you were — the same use-case as a back button in a browser. If you want one-press exit no matter what, pop everything first with the `⌂` button and Esc once.

!!! Are external links followed normally?

Yes — only links that resolve to a tiddler in the wiki trigger a deep-dive. Anything else (URLs, mailto, anchors that don't resolve) falls through to the browser's default handling.

